  <h2>Nova Scotia Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Nova Scotia’s growing season is shaped by maritime influence. The ocean moderates extreme
    temperatures, but it also slows spring warming and limits peak summer heat compared to
    inland continental regions. Success here often comes from steady planning rather than
    chasing early planting dates.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Spring warming can be gradual</h3>
  <p>
    Coastal air keeps temperatures stable, but soil can remain cool well into late spring.
    Warm-season crops planted too early often sit without growing.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're unsure whether it’s safe to transplant, this guide explains
    <a href="/guides/when-to-transplant-seedlings-outdoors/">
      when seedlings are truly ready for outdoor conditions
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Summer heat is moderate, not extreme</h3>
  <p>
    While frost-free windows can be decent in coastal zones, total growing degree day
    accumulation may be lower than gardeners expect. Heat-loving crops mature more slowly
    than in hotter inland provinces.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Choose shorter-maturity varieties.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Use the sunniest, most sheltered locations for warm crops.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) Interior vs. coastal differences</h3>
  <p>
    Inland valleys may accumulate more heat but also carry slightly higher frost risk.
    Coastal gardens benefit from moderation but may sacrifice peak heat.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Fall cooling is steady but real</h3>
  <p>
    Late summer transitions gradually into cooler nights. Warm-season crops slow once
    overnight temperatures trend downward, even before frost officially arrives.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're pushing late plantings, this explains
    <a href="/guides/when-is-it-too-late-to-plant-for-fall-harvest/">
      how to judge whether it’s too late for a fall harvest
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Start with frost timing and remaining seasonal heat for your nearest station.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to realistic heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you garden inland or in a low-lying frost pocket.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Nova Scotia, steady heat accumulation and realistic variety choice matter more than
    pushing early or late extremes.
  </p>
</section>